= About PhenomeCentral =
{{box cssClass="floatinginfobox" title="**Contents**"}} {{toc depth="3"/}} {{/box}}
PhenomeCentral is a repository for secure data sharing targeted to clinicians and scientists working in the rare disorder community. PhenomeCentral encourages global scientific collaboration while respecting the privacy of patients profiled in this centralized database.
== Why is it useful? == (% class="section-1" %)((( ; PhenomeCentral enables the **discovery of multiple individuals affected by the same unnamed disorder** : Undiagnosed disorders may be present in only a handful of individuals seen at different hospitals and sequenced by different centers. The PhenomeCentral collaboration model enables effective and secure data-sharing techniques that allow clinicians and scientists to learn about the existence of cases similar to theirs, which eventually may help improve the understanding of disorder manifestations and confirm the underlying cause. ; The matching algorithms are **sensitive to atypical phenotypic manifestations of disorders** : The semantic model which is the basis of our matching process helps reveal subtle similarities between disorder manifestations and may provide justification for reconsidering diagnoses that were initially discarded due to atypical phenotypes. )))
== Who is contributing to PhenomeCentral? == (% class="section-1" %)((( [[Several major rare disease research programs>>Groups.WebHome]], including the Canadian [[CARE for RARE>>Groups.Care4Rare]] Project, the [[RD-Connect>>http://rd-connect.eu]] Project and the [[NIH Undiagnosed Diseases Program>>Groups.UDP]], are contributing interesting cases to PhenomeCentral, in order to help build an extensive rare disorder knowledge base and to establish collaborations that may help find the underlying genetic cause of unsolved cases. PhenomeCentral currently has {{comment}}$services.query.hql(', BaseObject u where u.name = doc.fullName and u.className = ''XWiki.XWikiUsers'' and exists (from XWikiDocument p, BaseObject po where p.creator = doc.fullName and p.fullName = po.name and po.className = ''PhenoTips.PatientClass'')').count(){{/comment}}{{velocity}}$services.query.hql(', BaseObject u where u.name = doc.fullName and u.className = ''XWiki.XWikiUsers''').count(){{/velocity}} members who have contributed hundreds of cases that are available via [[phenotype matching>>path:#HDiscoveringsimilarcases]] once users enter their patient data. Additionally, all registered users have view-only access to cases that have been made public by other members. )))
== How to use PhenomeCentral == (% class="section-1" %)((( Registered PhenomeCentral users can * [[view available public data>>path:#HBrowsingtheavailabledata]], * [[contribute new cases>>path:#HDataentry]], * [[discover other patients with manifestations similar to theirs>>path:#HDiscoveringsimilarcases]] which may help them gain more insight into or even solve undiagnosed cases, * [[establish collaborations>>path:#HAddingcollaboratorstoyourcases]], * [[share scientific information>>path:#HInitiatingcontactwiththeownerofanon-publiccase]] with other contributors.
=== Browsing the available data === (% class="section-2" %)((( The PhenomeCentral homepage provides quick access to all information of interest for using the system: (% style="width: 48%; float: left" %)((( ==== Left column: your data ==== * The **My data** box lists the cases owned by the current user. Please read below for more information about [[data ownership>>path:#HCaseownership]]. * The **Data shared with me** box lists the cases for which the current user is a collaborator either because he or she is part of the group which owns the case, or because the owner explicitly listed them as a collaborator on that case. Please read below for more information about [[specifying collaborators>>path:#HAddingcollaboratorstoyourcases]]. )))(% style="width: 48%; float: right" %)((( ==== Right column: public data ==== * The **Public data** lists the cases that are available to all registered users, for viewing without restrictions. )))(% class="clearfloats" %)((()))
[[image:@pc-homepage-panels.png||width=100%]]
The homepage is immediately accessible from any other page by clicking on the PhenomeCentral logo or on the home icon ( [[{{icon name="home" /}}>>Main.WebHome]]) displayed at the bottom of the page header area.
[[image:@pc-header-home.png]] )))
=== Data entry === (% class="section-2" %)((( PhenomeCentral relies on the [[PhenoTips>>http://phenotips.org]] software for data entry and storage. PhenoTips enables data capture and storage using the standardized vocabulary defined by the [[Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO)>>http://human-phenotype-ontology.org]]. PhenomeCentral relies on the semantic phenotype relations defined by the ontology to identify the most relevant patient profile matches and to help users discover clusters of patients that may suffer from the same disorder.
Phenotypes can be selected from a predefined list of common manifestations, or by searching the entire ontology using the Quick Phenotype Search field for the relevant manifestations that users have observed in their patients. A phenotype can be marked as **observed (Y)**, **not observed and relevant (N)**, or **not observed and/or not investigated, i.e. irrelevant (NA)**. It is not necessary to specify that a phenotype listed in the form is NOT present, unless the information about its absence is considered particularly relevant. Each phenotype can be annotated with information such as **age of onset** and **pace of progression**, which will help narrow down the possible diagnoses and find the most relevant phenotype matches in the database. It is important to know that while free-form text can be entered, these entries are not searchable or matchable within the registry. Therefore, users are encouraged to provide detailed phenotypic descriptions using ontology terms, as more precision will lead to a more accurate knowledge base for the community, as well as to better case match results for the contributor.
[[image:@pc-phenotype.png]]
Entries owned by a contributor can be accessed at any time via the "My data" box displayed on the homepage. Users can also modify or delete the patient profiles via the patient report menu available on the right side of the page. )))
=== Case ownership === (% class="section-2" %)((( By default, you are the owner of any data that you have entered in the repository. Owners of a case can edit the case, choose to share the case will collaborators, and manage the case. Under certain circumstances, you may wish to transfer ownership of a case to a larger consortium if you and your case become part of a wider study, or to another PhenomeCentral contributor if for any reason he or she becomes responsible for following that specific patient.
When viewing or editing a case, the owner is displayed at the top of the page. Ownership can be modified by the owner, i.e. transferred to one of the owner's groups or to another user:
[[image:@pc-view-ownership.png]]
[[image:@pc-change-ownership-dialog.png]] )))
=== Establishing visibility === (% class="section-2" %)((( PhenomeCentral supports three major levels of data visibility: * {{icon name="private" /}} **private**: hidden from everyone except the owner and their explicit [[collaborators>>path:#HAddingcollaboratorstoyourcases]] * {{icon name="matchable" /}} **matchable**: the record cannot be directly viewed or searched by registered users, but is available to the automated phenotype matching algorithm. This allows for registered users to be aware of the case if it is a match for other similar cases. See [[Discovering similar cases>>path:#HDiscoveringsimilarcases]]. * {{icon name="public" /}} **public**: viewable and searchable by all registered users
By default, cases are set to be **matchable**. It is important to note that a case's visibility refers to how users are able to view the case and does not determine editing or managing capabilities.
When viewing or editing a case, the visibility is displayed at the top of the page. Visibility can be modified by the case owner:
[[image:@pc-view-visibility.png]]
[[image:@pc-change-visibility-dialog.png]] )))
=== Adding collaborators to your cases === (% class="section-2" %)((( Adding collaborators you to give a **trusted** colleague access to one of your non-public cases, as well as allowing you to give your colleague editing capabilities to any of your cases. When viewing or editing a case, the number of collaborators is displayed at the top of the page. Collaborators can be awarded different levels of access to the case, ensuring the collaborator's ability to either: * **view** the full patient profile * **view** and **modify** the patient data * **view** and **modify** the patient data, as well as **manage** collaborators (invite other collaborators, terminate collaborations, change collaborators' access levels)
[[image:@pc-view-collaborators.png]]
[[image:@pc-change-collaborators-dialog.png]] )))
=== Discovering similar cases === (% class="section-2" %)((( Owners of **matchable** and **public** cases can see the existing matchable and public cases that are most similar to theirs. PhenomeCentral uses an algorithm that assesses the similarity of accessible cases based on the entered phenotypes that the users have provided (the selected [[Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO)>>http://human-phenotype-ontology.org]] terms). The algorithm prioritizes cases that are matches for greater numbers of terms, the informativeness of the matched terms (i.e. rare phenotypes as assessed by numerous sources), and the similarity of entered terms within the [[Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO)>>http://human-phenotype-ontology.org]]. For example, cases that share the term "oculomotor apraxia" would be a better match than cases that share the term "intellectual disability", while the algorithm will recognize that "intellectual disability" and "global developmental delay" are terms that share some phenotypic similarity, though they are not exact matches.
After entering a case, contributors can see the most similar cases found in the database displayed at the bottom of the page. The list is re-generated each time the user accesses their case and may change as more data is added or modified to that case or to other cases in the database. **Public** cases that are similar are displayed without restrictions, while for **matchable** cases the features that have contributed to the high similarity score at hinted at without disclosing any specific information.
**Private cases do not participate in any way in the similarity matching process**: if your case is private you will not be able to see similar cases and private cases will not be included in the list of matching similar cases for any other users. If you wish to benefit from the system's similarity feature, please consider giving your cases at least the {{icon name="matchable" /}}**matchable** visibility level.
[[image:pc-similarity.png]] )))
=== Initiating contact with the owner of a non-public case === (% class="section-2" %)((( As the owners of matchable cases are not disclosed, the system allows users to initiate contact without disclosing any actual contact information:
[[image:@pc-undisclosed-match.png]]
The recipient will receive a notification email which he or she may chose to answer or ignore. ))) )))
== Questions? == (% class="section-1" %)((( Please address your questions or report issues encountered while using PhenomeCentral to ##support@phenomecentral.org##. )))
